  "prompt": "Did anybody ever document what the Dodo bird of Mauritius tasted like?",
  "response": "Yes, there are historical accounts that describe the taste of the Dodo bird (*Raphus cucullatus*), an extinct flightless bird native to Mauritius. The Dodo was first encountered by European sailors in the late 16th century, and some of these early visitors recorded their impressions of the bird and its meat.\n\nOne of the most commonly cited descriptions comes from **Sir Thomas Herbert**, an English traveler who visited Mauritius in the early 17th century. In his 1634 book *\"A Relation of Some Yeares Travaille\"*, he described the Dodo as having \"repulsive\" flesh, but other accounts suggest this may have been an exaggeration. Another report, from Dutch sailor **Willem van West-Zanen** in 1602, stated that the bird's meat was tough and greasy, though not necessarily unpalatable.\n\nIt's important to note that sailors often cooked the Dodo by boiling it, which may not have brought out the best flavor. Additionally, the Dodo was a large, flightless bird with a diet primarily of fruits and seeds, which might have influenced the taste of its meat.\n\nOverall, the descriptions of the Dodo's taste are mixed, but they generally suggest that it was not particularly delicious, which may have contributed to its decline and eventual extinction by the late 17th century.",
